  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 5:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Jesus when He saw the man lying and had ascertained (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "γνοὺς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", having learned from the man or his friends) that already he had passed a long time (in that infirmity) says: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "θέλεις ὑγιὴς γενέσθαι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; “Do you wish to become whole (healthy)?” This question was put to attract the man’s attention and awaken hope. But the man is hopeless: it is not a question of will, he says, but of opportunity. His very weakness enabled others to anticipate him; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐν ᾧ ἔρχομαι ἐγὼ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “while I am coming,” he could, then, move a little, but not quickly enough. At each bubbling up of the water, apparently only one could be healed. The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἄλλος πρὸ ἐμοῦ καταβαίνει",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " was a great aggravation of his case.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "knew",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "perceived",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", perhaps supernaturally (see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 16:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but He might learn it from the bystanders: the fact was very likely notorious.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Wilt thou?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Or, more strongly, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Dost thou will",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "? Note that the man does not ask first. Here and in the case of the man born blind (9), as also of Malchus’ ear (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 22:51",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), Christ heals without being asked to do so. Excepting the healing of the royal official’s son all Christ’s miracles in the Fourth Gospel are spontaneous. On no other occasion does Christ ask a question without being addressed first: why does He now ask a question of which the answer was so obvious? Probably in order to rouse the sick man out of his lethargy and despondency. It was the first step towards the man’s having sufficient faith: he must be inspired with some expectation of being cured. The question has nothing to do with religious scruples; ‘Art thou willing to be made whole, although it is the Sabbath?’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
